Ted:

I&#39;m no linguist either, and I hesitated to mention colors in my post.  I 
just used that example to help illustrate my point.  Obviously, color 
vision involve the cones in the retina as you wrote and is not something 
learned.  However, to digress, I have read that cultures divide the 
visible light spectrum differently concerning how far a given color is 
considered to extend.

It seemed to me that the placement of the lips and tongue in &quot;Awl&quot; vs. 
&quot;On&quot; was clearly different and that sound should be audible to another 
English speaker.  &quot;Awl&quot; requires rounded lips and the tongue must be 
pushed farther forward than its position for &quot;on.&quot;  In your Chinese 
example, you state that the Chinese have difficulty distinguishing 
between L and R.  Is it that they cannot hear the difference because 
their language doesn&#39;t require it or that they don&#39;t know the proper 
placement of the vocal apparatus in order to produce the the two 
separate sounds?

Your description of the different Hindi sounds seems more subtle than 
what I was talking about.  Do you think that is wrong, or is the 
apparent subtlety simply because we don&#39;t make those distinctions?

Paige

P.S. thanks for the interesting tidbit about brown.

